                <h2>Case Opening: The 2 AM Account Suspension Notice</h2>
<p>Zhou, the operations lead of a utility app's overseas team, received an email from Google Ads at 2 AM. The subject line read "Your account has been suspended" for violating the "Circumventing Systems policy."</p>
<p>Zhou's first reaction was "We didn't do anything wrong." But after calming down, he discovered the root cause: over 50 ad creatives uploaded last week all used the same template structure with just product and copy variations.</p>
<p>This is a typical "false positive" scenario. Google's automated systems sometimes flag similar ad structures as circumvention, but preparing appeal materials is far more than writing an email.</p>
<hr />
<h2>Problem Breakdown: Common Triggers for Account Suspension</h2>
<p>Before preparing appeal materials, you must understand "why" the suspension happened. Google Ads account suspensions typically fall into these categories:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Circumventing Systems</strong>: Similar creatives, frequent landing page changes, redirects</li>
<li><strong>Misleading Content</strong>: Ad copy doesn't match landing page, exaggerated claims</li>
<li><strong>Brand Infringement</strong>: Unauthorized use of trademarks, logos, or copyrighted content</li>
<li><strong>Targeting Minors</strong>: Targeting users under 18 or sensitive content</li>
<li><strong>Payment Issues</strong>: Credit card fraud alerts, billing address mismatches, outstanding balance</li>
</ul>
<blockquote>
<p>Diagnosis Tip: If the email specifies the violation type, you can directly prepare corresponding materials. If it only shows "account-level suspension," check the "Policy center" in Google Ads backend for specific violation details.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h2>Action Plan: Three-Step Checklist for Appeal Materials</h2>
<h3>Step 1: Collect Your "Evidence Package"</h3>
<p>Before appealing, prepare these materials organized by folder:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Account screenshots</strong>: Include account ID, current status, violation notes</li>
<li><strong>Campaign screenshots</strong>: Suspended campaigns and ad groups</li>
<li><strong>Violation details screenshots</strong>: Specific violation descriptions from Google policy page</li>
<li><strong>Backend operation records</strong>: If creative changes were made, prepare before/after comparisons</li>
</ol>
<h3>Step 2: Draft Your Appeal Email</h3>
<p>The appeal email is the core of your materials. A qualified appeal should include three parts:</p>
<p><strong>① Problem Statement</strong>: Briefly describe what happened in 1-2 sentences. No excuses or emotional language.</p>
<p><strong>② Root Cause Analysis</strong>: Honestly explain the underlying reason for the violation. If it was a false positive, provide evidence explaining why the system was wrong.</p>
<p><strong>③ Remediation Commitment</strong>: Clearly list corrective actions taken or planned, giving Google a "foreseeable change."</p>
<pre><code>Email Template Framework:
- Opening: Account ID + Violation type + Request for re-review
- Body: Violation reason + Remediation steps + Prevention measures
- Closing: Appreciation + Hope to resume advertising
</code></pre>
<h3>Step 3: Submit Through Official Channels</h3>
<p>Login to Google Ads → Settings → Account Access → Appeals option → Upload materials and submit.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Note: The appeal portal is usually hidden at the bottom of the policy page. If you can't find it, access it directly here: <a href="https://support.google.com/google-ads/troubleshooter/2893932">Google Ads Policy Appeals Center</a></p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h2>Outcome Tracking: Two Possibilities Within 48 Hours</h2>
<p>Zhou's team submitted their appeal materials the next morning. With thorough preparation, they clearly stated "similar creatives were due to batch upload requirements, not intentional circumvention," and attached before/after comparisons of modified materials.</p>
<p><strong>First Outcome (Smooth Restoration)</strong>: Email notification within 48 hours, account restored. This typically happens when violations are minor and explanations are clear.</p>
<p><strong>Second Outcome (Additional Materials Requested)</strong>: Reply requesting additional proof. Zhou was later asked for "compliance certification documents for the target market." After submitting privacy policy links and export compliance declarations, the account was restored on the third day.</p>
<p><strong>Third Outcome (Appeal Rejected)</strong>: If rejected, wait 30 days before submitting a new appeal. During this period, thoroughly investigate account issues and don't repeat the same appeal logic.</p>
<hr />
<h2>Key Takeaways: Five Points for Appeal Preparation</h2>
<ol>
<li><strong>Don't submit appeals at 2 AM</strong>: Appeals submitted during business hours on weekdays typically have higher processing priority</li>
<li><strong>Materials should include "comparisons"</strong>: Before/after images are more persuasive than text explanations</li>
<li><strong>Appeal reasons must be specific</strong>: Avoid vague statements like "We've always been compliant"</li>
<li><strong>Prepare supplementary materials</strong>: Google sometimes requests business licenses, App Store links, etc.</li>
<li><strong>Don't run heavy campaigns immediately after restoration</strong>: Test with small budgets for 3-5 days first to confirm account stability</li>
</ol>
<hr />
<p>If you're facing a Google Ads account suspension, first check the backend to confirm the violation reason, then prepare appeal materials according to the checklist above. Thorough preparation significantly increases your chances of successful appeal.</p>
